<br>
So some mages want to be #2 in nukes, behind wizards and above druids.  <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>Why?</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->  Can you give me a reason?<br>
<br>
I can give you a reason why it <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>might</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> be acceptable for druids to nuke more than mages.  Namely, that our pets, except in some cases, provide so much more additional damage above and beyond our nukes, that in order to be acceptable damage dealers, druids need stronger nukes.  Remember: surplus support classes, such as healers and buffers, yield diminishing returns, whereas each additional damage dealer reduces the length of the fight by so many seconds.<br>
<br>
I don't care whether <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Mage nuke &gt;&gt; Druid nuke</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
I <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>do</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> care that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Mage damage output &gt;&gt; Druid damage output</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, since <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Druid Utility &gt;&gt; Mage Utility</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  the small DD gap is easily made up and more by the pets...for druids on raids, a lot of them are secondary healers (tertiary or worse), and many are reduced to nuking, so they should have decent DPS<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Your druid friend is exactly right.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  in raids, pets are strictly not allowed.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Whoever you are raiding with is living in the past.  There are some places where pets still do not make sense, and against some targets they lack punch, but for most situations, raiding without pets is like tying your good hand behind your back.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  Wizards should rule BOTH long-term and short-term DD output.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->I think many would dispute whether it <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>should</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> be the case, and it is certainly <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>not</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> the case now.<br>
<br>
I think you would find regular visits to <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://pub23.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation">Graffë's Wizard Discussion</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> enlightening, especially the class balance forum.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  Until the Magician ran OOM. The Wizzie would still have some punch left then.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->The opposite is true.  First of all, one avoids going OOM unless absolutely necessary.  The differences in damage per mana hardly matter in so far as determining who runs out of mana first.   Indeed, you could argue that faster nukes mean a wizard will OOM first.  But rarely is burning all your mana consistantly a smart move.  And aggro usually limits nuke more than mana, as wizards well know.<br>
<br>
Second, an OOM mage still has <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Gobaner</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> while an OOM wizard has his butt to sit on.  Alternately both have right-click nukes available to them.  Mages have more than one way to regenerate mana quickly if needed, especially rods of transvergence.  Wizards are far more limited by their mana than mages are.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  So with all 3 classes side-by-side, the druid would go OOM first<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->This comparison means less than one might think.  Rarely will it be rational to simply burn down one's mana bar.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  if our pets ARE good enough, and can be used on ENOUGH mobs, then the balance would be shifted to more equal mage/druid DDing<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->I do not see how this follows.  The better are pets are, the more convincing the druid call for better nukes is, assuming other druid capabilities remain relatively constant.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  IMO Necros should be the kings of long-term damage/mana ratio, with multiple necros's DoTs stacking<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Necromancers have a long list of legitimate complaints, and the inability to stack DoTs or something equivalent means they have traded their mortal souls for some shoddy merchandise.  I do not pretend to know what is required for necros, except that improvements to pets would help them and something needs to be done about the inability to stack DoTs.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  druids are a priest class, they are not designed to deal quick damage in full burn<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Yes, in an ideal world, perhaps.  It does seem odd that druids nuke so well being priests.  However, in the game as it is played, the other priest classes make druids largely redundant.  Almost everything they do is down <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>much</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> better by others.  Direct damage being to casters and to priests what combat is to melee classes, there is little alternative to giving druids decent nukes.<br>
<br>
Again, talk to some 60 druids and ask them how they like life in the end game.<br>
<br>
As to where we should stand in comparison to melee, I am not certain enough to offer definite opinions.  I do know rogues and monks are two classes that understand the game mechanics very well, and react effectively to threats to their position.  I would not bet money on anyone outdamaging rogues, except Wizards under special circumstances.  Assassination is a perfectly fine melee <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  &quot;burn down.&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
